<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Those persons tried under the death penalty in <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> MOST</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> states are those who have commited crimes so heinous, as to be considered atrocities. And those who are mass or serial murderers, killing usually FAR more than one person.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Did your brother stab someone to death so badly they were hard to identify?  Did he murder his wife, keep her in a freezer for a month, then cut her into pieces and chop her up in a woodchipper (this was done by an airline pilot to his stewardess wife in the eastern US)?  Did he cut his wife into little bitty pieces while she was Unconscious (not dead mind you, just unconscious, until he got to her vital organs), put all the pieces in trash bags, and leave her in a field for someone to find?  (This was done to a girl I went to school with cause her husband didnt like that she was divorcing his abusive ass, and he had been raised that women were chattel, so it was alright for him to do this to her.)  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> NO!!!!</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> your brother did none of these things.  These are things that are considered in the USA as heinous enough to deserve the death penalty.<br>
<br>
Or maybe he killed his wife, sons, daughters, mother, father, sister and brother.  Or maybe he went across the country raping, mutilating, and killing young children or young women.  These are MASS MURDERS, and SERIAL KILLINGS.  These are things that are considered in the USA as deserving of the death penalty.<br>
<br>
But ONLY after this person is found guilty BEYOND A REASONABLE DOUBT using ALL that current science can find to prove that this person did it.<br>
<br>
You have every right not to agree with it, but at least learn what it is your talking about before you attempt to use it in an argument.<br>
<br>
Was your brother forced to drive drunk?  No.  Did he know that what he was doing was wrong when he drove the vehicle while his license was suspended?  Yes.  Don't give me some sob story that he couldnt have found some other way to get to his wife.  That would be nothing but an excuse.  If it was that important, he could have found SOMEONE to take him to his wife, without driving his vehicle.  So yes, your brother is a criminal, for the time that he serves his sentence, and hopefully learns a hard lesson from it.  If your brother is old enough to marry, drive, and drink, then he is also old enough to know that his actions have consequences.<br>
<br>
Does he deserve the death penalty?  HELL NO.  And no where in the US that I know of would anyone feel any different.  You are attempting to compare apples and oranges.  When you want to compare Apples and Apples, or Oranges and Oranges then come back with a reasonable argument. <p><HTML><BODY>
